// Mayan gods × 12 — Itzamna and the cosmic sovereigns, the storm/maize/trade
// sustenance band, and the Hero Twins + Xibalba lords of the Popol Vuh.
// SEO funnel at /gab44/mayan-gods (index) + /gab44/mayan-gods/{slug}.
//
// FIFTEENTH pantheon on gab44. Completes the pre-Columbian Americas trilogy
// (Aztec ✦ Inca ✦ Maya) — the third leg of the Mesoamerican-and-Andean
// civilizational triangle. Where Aztec is the youngest fully-documented
// great pantheon with first-generation conquistador ethnography, and Inca
// the Andean state-cult of the brief 1438-1532 empire, Maya is the OLDEST
// continuously-attested Mesoamerican religious tradition — Preclassic
// Olmec roots c. 1200 BCE, Classic-period (250-900 CE) glyph-inscriptions
// on stelae across Tikal/Palenque/Copán/Yaxchilán, Postclassic Yucatán
// reconfiguration (c. 900-1521), and continuous-living-tradition among
// approximately 7 million Maya speakers across Guatemala / Yucatán /
// Chiapas / Belize / Honduras today.
//
// Source corpus per page: the Popol Vuh (the K'iche' Maya creation-and-Hero-
// Twins narrative, copied c. 1554-1558 by anonymous K'iche' nobles in
// Roman-script-K'iche' from older hieroglyphic codices and the Francisco
// Ximénez Spanish parallel-translation of c. 1701-1703; the only
// substantially-complete pre-Columbian Mesoamerican mythological text);
// the Dresden Codex (one of four surviving Postclassic Maya bark-paper
// books, c. 1200-1250 CE, astronomical-Venus-tables-eclipse-prediction);
// the Madrid Codex (Postclassic almanac, c. 1400 CE); the Paris Codex
// (Postclassic ritual-calendar, c. 1450 CE); the Grolier Codex (the
// 4th surviving codex, authenticated 2018); the Books of Chilam Balam
// (Postclassic-and-colonial Yucatec almanacs, especially Chumayel,
// Mani, Tizimin); the Annals of the Cakchiquels; Bishop Diego de
// Landa's *Relación de las cosas de Yucatán* (1566, the same Landa
// who burned the Mani codices on 12 July 1562, then wrote the only
// surviving guide to Yucatec script while in Spain awaiting Inquisition
// trial); the Classic-period glyph-inscriptions on stelae, lintels, and
// painted ceramics across Tikal / Palenque / Copán / Yaxchilán /
// Bonampak / Calakmul. Modern scholarship: Linda Schele and David
// Freidel's *A Forest of Kings* (1990) and *Maya Cosmos* (1993),
// Michael Coe's *The Maya* (now in its 9th edition), Dennis Tedlock's
// *Popol Vuh* translation (1985, revised 1996), Karl Taube's *Aztec
// and Maya Myths* (1993) and *The Major Gods of Ancient Yucatan*
// (1992), Stephen Houston and Karl Taube's *The Memory of Bones* (2006),
// David Stuart's *The Order of Days* (2011), Allen Christenson's
// *Popol Vuh* translation (2007), Simon Martin and Nikolai Grube's
// *Chronicle of the Maya Kings and Queens* (2008).
//
// Three families × 4 gods:
//
//   1. Cosmic Sovereigns (Itzamna, Ix Chel, Kukulkan, Kinich Ahau) —
//      the supreme creator-scribe, the moon-midwife-weaver, the
//      feathered-serpent of Chichén Itzá and the K'iche' Q'uq'umatz,
//      and the sun-face daytime-lord.
//
//   2. Storm, Maize, Forest, Trade (Chaak, Yum Kaax, Ek Chuah, Hun
//      Hunahpu) — the four-cardinal-direction rain-god whose
//      lightning-axe is the canonical Maya storm; the Foliated Maize
//      God who is the people themselves (the Popol Vuh creation-of-
//      humans-from-maize-dough); the black-god of merchants and cacao
//      whose name was the bag-on-the-back of every traveling pochteca;
//      the Maize-Father whose decapitation by the Xibalba lords sets
//      up the entire Popol Vuh.
//
//   3. Hero Twins & Xibalba (Hunahpu, Xbalanque, Ah Puch, Camazotz) —
//      the two sons of Hun Hunahpu and Xquic, who descend to Xibalba
//      to defeat the death-lords and ascend as Sun and Moon (Hunahpu
//      = sun, Xbalanque = jaguar-deer-moon); plus the two most-iconic
//      Xibalba lords, Ah Puch (death-skull-with-bell-rattles) and
//      Camazotz (the killer-bat of the House of Bats, the only Xibalba
//      trial that successfully decapitates Hunahpu before his
//      resurrection).
//
// Shadow-honest: each page names (a) the 12 July 1562 auto-da-fé at
// Maní where Bishop Diego de Landa burned 27 Maya codices and 5,000
// "idols" before the rebuilt church-on-temple-site of Maní — the most
// catastrophic single act of book-burning in the documented history of
// the Americas, leaving only 4 surviving Maya codices out of an
// estimated 1000s; (b) the Conquest of Yucatán (Francisco de Montejo,
// 1527-1546) and the Conquest of K'iche' Highlands (Pedro de
// Alvarado, 1524 — defeating Tecún Umán in single combat at
// El Pinar de Quetzaltenango, Tecún Umán now the Guatemalan national
// hero whose face is on the 0.50-quetzal banknote); the 1697 fall of
// Nojpetén (the last independent Maya capital, on the island in Lake
// Petén-Itzá, defeated by Martín de Ursúa 200 years after the rest
// of Mesoamerica fell); (c) the Caste War of Yucatán (1847-1901, the
// longest indigenous war of resistance in modern Latin American
// history — Maya peasants under Cecilio Chi and Jacinto Pat nearly
// expelled all non-Maya from Yucatán before being pushed back to
// Chan Santa Cruz, an autonomous Maya state in the Quintana Roo
// forest that survived until 1901 under the *Cruz Parlante*
// talking-cross oracle-tradition); (d) the Guatemalan Civil War
// (1960-1996) genocidal-phase under General Efraín Ríos Montt
// (1982-1983) which the 1999 UN Truth Commission found constituted
// genocide against Maya Ixil, K'iche', and Q'eqchi' populations —
// 200,000+ killed, 626 massacres documented, Maya identity itself
// the explicit target; Rigoberta Menchú's 1992 Nobel Peace Prize
// being the international recognition of this; (e) the 2012-apocalypse
// hoax — the misreading of the Long Count *13.0.0.0.0* date of
// 21-December-2012 as "Maya prophesied the end of the world" — a
// pure-New-Age confabulation rejected by every contemporary Maya
// elder and Maya scholar, but which produced $200M+ in tourism and
// book-sales and the Roland Emmerich *2012* film (2009); the actual
// Maya understanding (multiple Long Count cycles before and after
// 2012, no apocalyptic content, simply a calendrical-period transition)
// was systematically buried by the marketing-budget; (f) the New-Age
// appropriation of Hunab Ku as "the one Maya god" — Hunab Ku does
// NOT appear in any pre-Conquest Maya source; the term is found only
// in the colonial-era Chilam Balam books written 100+ years after
// Conquest, and modern Mayanists consider Hunab Ku a Franciscan
// translation-attempt to make Maya religion monotheist-compatible
// rather than a genuine pre-Columbian deity (Karl Taube has been
// explicit on this); the Hunab-Ku-flat-symbol marketed on Cancún
// jewelry is itself a 1996 invention by José Argüelles, not an
// ancient symbol; (g) the appropriation of Kukulkan / Q'uq'umatz as
// "the same god as Quetzalcoatl" — they share the feathered-serpent
// iconography and likely a substrate connection through Postclassic
// trade and the Toltec influence on Chichén Itzá, but each tradition
// holds distinct ritual-cycle, distinct calendar-mathematics, and
// distinct cosmological roles; the flattening into "the Mesoamerican
// feathered serpent" loses both; (h) the Chichén Itzá El Castillo
// equinox-serpent-shadow tourist-phenomenon (the staircase shadow
// that looks like a snake-descending on March-and-September equinox)
// — a real architectural-astronomical effect, but the Hollywood
// staging of it as "the day Kukulkan returns" is largely a
// late-20th-century INAH tourism-product, not a pre-Columbian ritual;
// (i) Mel Gibson's *Apocalypto* (2006) presenting an essentially
// fictional Maya-collapse narrative timed to the Spanish arrival
// (the Classic Maya collapse was c. 800-1000 CE, six centuries
// before Spanish arrival; Gibson telescopes them for cinematic
// effect, then has a Maya elder character explicitly state "your
// time is ending" as the conquistador ships arrive — a colonial-
// providential reading of Maya history that Maya scholars and elders
// uniformly rejected); (j) the contemporary appropriation of Maya
// calendar by ayahuasca-tourism and "13-Moon Dreamspell" Argüelles-
// derived workshops in Tulum/Bali/Goa — none of which use the
// actual Maya tzolkin-260-day count, all of which charge $400-$2000
// for "Maya initiations" from non-Maya facilitators; the Guatemalan
// Maya elder-assembly (Oxlajuj Ajpop) has issued multiple statements
// rejecting this; (k) the 1492-and-after "discovered America" framing
// that erases the fact that Maya cities reached >100,000-person urban
// density (Tikal, El Mirador) more than a millennium before any
// European city did, and the Maya glyph-writing system was a
// fully-logosyllabic literate script (decoded by Yuri Knorozov
// 1952 + David Stuart + Linda Schele 1980s) on a par with Chinese
// and Egyptian script — a fact the standard US-Eurocentric
// "uncivilized natives" history of the Americas still routinely
// obscures.

